explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER — The macro/inline used to validate sock_id and sock_name may contain side-effects (calls, logging, assertion, early return/abort) or be compiled-out to a no-op. To decide if the parameter-check operations executed in the function are dead, you must know whether this expands to code that affects program behaviour (e.g. returns/abort/logs) or is removed entirely.

OS_ObjectIdFindByName — The single substantive call in the function; you must know its effects (return values, whether it modifies *sock_id, global state, or causes other side-effects). If it has no side-effects and its return value is unused by callers, the call might be dead; conversely, if it updates state, removal would change behaviour.

LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE — This argument to OS_ObjectIdFindByName can change the behaviour of that routine. Knowing its value/definition is required to determine what OS_ObjectIdFindByName does for this call and whether the call has observable effects.

osal_id_t — The out-parameter type for sock_id. Its definition determines whether writing through the pointer produces observable effects (e.g. triggers volatile writes, contains resources/handles), which bears on whether those writes are necessary or dead.

int32 — The return_code type (signed width and semantics) is required to understand return value handling and whether any cast/truncation or platform-specific behaviour could make the assignment/return a no-op.

OS_printf — Included because OS_CHECK_POINTER or related debug/validation code commonly calls logging routines (such as OS_printf). If logging occurs, removing the checks would remove observable output, so you need OS_printf's behaviour (side-effects, whether it's a no-op in some builds) to decide if the checks are dead.

Note: If OS_ObjectIdFindByName internally calls other routines that have side-effects (e.g. OS_ObjectIdGetByName, OS_ObjectIdRelease), the definitions of those symbols would also be required; include them if the initial inspection of OS_ObjectIdFindByName indicates they contribute observable behaviour.
